{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-render-openai-gym-on-windows-65767ab52ae2", "time": 1683017780.653907, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-render-openai-gym-on-windows-65767ab52ae2/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to Render OpenAI-Gym on Windows | by Jian Xu | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to Render OpenAI-Gym on Windows", "description": "OpenAI Gym is a great place to study and develop reinforced learning algorithms. It provides lots of interesting games (so called \u201cenvironments\u201d) that you can put your strategy to test. For example\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://gym.openai.com/", "anchor_text": "OpenAI Gym", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://github.com/ageron/handson-ml2/blob/master/18_reinforcement_learning.ipynb", "anchor_text": "Chapter 18 reinforced learning notebook", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://github.com/jianxu305/openai-gym-docker", "anchor_text": "GitHub link", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://jupyter-docker-stacks.readthedocs.io/en/latest/using/selecting.html", "anchor_text": "Jupyter Dock Stack", "paragraph_index": 11}], "all_paragraphs": ["OpenAI Gym is a great place to study and develop reinforced learning algorithms. It provides lots of interesting games (so called \u201cenvironments\u201d) that you can put your strategy to test. For example, it has simple games like balancing a vertical pole on a little cart (\u201cCartPole-v1\u201d), swinging up a pendulum to upright position (\u201cPendulum-v0\u201d), as well as some classic video games like the Space Invader, and Pin Ball.", "However, the Gym is designed to run on Linux. Even though it can be installed on Windows using Conda or PIP, it cannot be visualized on Windows. If you run it on a headless server (such as a virtual machine on the cloud), then it needs PyVirtualDisplay, which doesn\u2019t work on Windows either. Therefore, playing the OpenAI Gym on Windows is inconvenient.", "So how can Windows users visualize the Gym?", "One easy solution is to use Google Colab. It\u2019s accessible through a web browser, and most packages are already set up properly. However, the free Colab is not without drawbacks:", "After using Colab for a while, I became more and more annoyed, especially when the Colab sessions crashes more often that I\u2019d like. Therefore, I started to consider alternative paths, but none of them seems particularly easy:", "After evaluating many options, I ended up building a minimalistic docker image myself. It\u2019s not nearly as hard as it sounds. But if you want to skip the work of setting up environment, you can directly enjoy playing the Gym in the following three easy steps:", "3. Run the docker image from command line (and mount your favorite files if you wish)", "or just launch from the Docker Desktop GUI", "For the convenience of testing, I included a small notebook in the image to test the rendering 6 example environments: Cart Pole v1, Mountain Car v0, Pendulum v0, Lunar Lander v2, Space Invaders v0, and Car Racing v0.", "In addition, I copied the Chapter 18 reinforced learning notebook from G\u00e9ron, Aur\u00e9lien\u2019s book: Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras, and TensorFlow. So anyone can immediately start playing with this excellent tutorial.", "If you are interested in how to make this docker, please read on. It\u2019s actually quite simple, all you need is a Dockerfile with less than 30 lines (GitHub link). Here I will go through the Dockerfile step-by-step.", "First, I started from the Jupyter Dock Stack to avoid building from scratch. Since G\u00e9ron\u2019s machine learning book uses tensorflow, I decided to build on top of the jupyter/tensorflow-notebook image.", "Next, install some libraries that are needed to render the environments.", "Then install the OpenAI Gym, as well as the PyVirtualDisplay.", "That\u2019s about it. With these few lines, you will be able to run and render G\u00e9ron\u2019s Chapter 18 reinforcement learning notebook, which uses the \u201cCart-Pole\u201d environment.", "I added a few more lines to the Dockerfile to support some environments that requires Box2D, Toy Text, and Atari. For example, the Classical Lunar Lander, and Space Invader environments.", "And the final two lines are just copying some files into the image for the convenience of testing.", "That\u2019s all for the Dockerfile. Building this simple docker is easy too, just run the following in command line:", "Congratulations! You just build your own OpenAI Gym docker! Now you can launch it with Docker Desktop and start playing with it.", "Happy exercising in the gym ;-)", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Engineer, teacher, writer. Loves to explain complex problems in simple terms, and to solve real-world problems by technology."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F65767ab52ae2&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-render-openai-gym-on-windows-65767ab52ae2&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-render-openai-gym-on-windows-65767ab52ae2&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text